1089646869482226074_1578026711	6/10/2015 9:20	52.516666667, 13.383333333	0	18	Normal	https://instagram.com/p/8fNA36GsGa/	So far this year a staggering 188.000 people have put their lives into the hands of smugglers to take them across the Mediterranean to Europe. For my project 'Travelling Light' I have asked them about their journeys and the items they had with them and what these items mean to them. Mohammad, 33, Auto Body Painter I bought the jeans and the shirt about two and a half years ago for Eid in Benghazi. When our house in Homs got destroyed in 2011 we moved there in the hope that we could return back home once the riots subsided. I still like to wear them except that now they are not just clothes but also memories of the journey. I remember spending that Eid in the garden with our friends and family. We had around twenty guests. It was ok but holidays in Syria are different, better. Back home weâ€™d go to visit people and go to parties and barbecues... The sports pants are from the same shop as the other clothes. I used to like going shopping there. Most other shops in Benghazi would only sell traditional Arabic clothes. The trousers are AC Milan, but I just bought them to walk around in. And besides... my favourite team is Bayern Munich. I wore those pants underneath my jeans. When it got hot I simply took the jeans off. And also, you canâ€™t take any spare clothes onto the ship, so the more you manage to wear when you get on, the better. Nearly everybody on the ship threw up. My children as well. But I ate nothing other than a few dates in the whole three days, just as the smuggler suggested, and I was fine. We got saved by an oil tanker. To get up on board we had to climb about fifteen metres up a rope ladder. We had to carry the children. I was very worried for them. To calm me down on the journey I was listening to Quran verse with those headphones. We had to leave everything behind but Iâ€™m not sad about that. Iâ€™m relieved that we are here now. Thank god it all went well. #travellinglightproject #WeAreAllHumans #refugeeswelcome #syriansineurope #worldrefugeeday #crisis #humanitywashedashore #refugeecrisis #aylan #reportagespotlight #flakphoto #theguardian #deutschland	https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xtp1/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/12070882_317932685048404_1789324617_n.jpg	humanitywashedashore, travellinglightproject, deutschland, reportagespotlight, theguardian, weareallhumans, refugeeswelcome, worldrefugeeday, refugeecrisis, flakphoto, crisis, aylan, syriansineurope	sonicetobeme	1578026711

1088318526786814525_1578026711	4/10/2015 13:21	48.1, 8.7	0	15	Normal	https://instagram.com/p/8ae-8XmsI9/	So far this year a staggering 188.000 people have put their lives into the hands of smugglers to take them across the Mediterranean to Europe. For my project 'Travelling Light' I have asked them about their journeys and the items they had with them and what these items mean to them. Ahmad, 36, Painter / Decorator I got the coat in my hometown of Aleppo. I bought it on the market not long before we left. Itâ€™s nice and warm. The shirt is also from Aleppo. I like checked shirts and I like the colour. The shirt and the jeans are both Syrian brands. I bought the little bag a day or two before we left Syria. I kept my money and the important documents in it and wore it under my clothes for the duration of the journey. To keep things safe. I got the card from the bank when I opened a new account about three years ago, but I needed all my money for the journey... I have only about 20 euros left in it. We sold everything we had to pay for the trip. We had to pay 200 dollars for someone to take us to Tunisia, then 700 dollars to get to Libya and 4000 dollars for a boat to Italy. In Italy I got beaten up because I refused to leave my fingerprints. In the end I had to. Why I have the card from the lawyer I donâ€™t know... it was just in the bag. The little incense stick was in my bag so my clothes would smell nice. The SIM cards are from Syria, Turkey, Algeria, Tunisia and Italy... all the countries we crossed on our journey. The little papers are entry documents for Turkey. When we get passport photos made in Syria, we usually get twelve at a time in a little envelope. I needed a few photos for some documents I had made in Syria and I gave one to a friend. The others are just souvenirs now. The woman in the other photo is my mum. The picture is nearly fifty years old. For my project 'Travelling Light' I have asked them about their journeys and the items they had with them and what these items mean to them. Hiam, 40, Teacher I wore the jumper underneath a light black coat. I was in a cabin with the children so I wasnâ€™t cold. But the coat did get wet and dirty, so I left it behind. I still usually wear a long jacket in public. The jumper is very comfortable. I got it on the Al-Hamidiya Market - a very good market in Damascus. I like nice clothes. All my clothes I had before we went on the journey I gave away to people in need. Leaving Egypt was my idea. My husband was scared but I was tired of moving from relatives to relatives because we had no home, so I decided that it would be best to take a boat to Europe. I had a good feeling. I thought either Iâ€™ll survive or Iâ€™ll die but at least my children will have the chance of a better future. My main motivation was a better future for my children. I never seriously believed that we could die until the last few hours on the boat... when I saw my children cry and scream I was questioning whether Iâ€™d made the right decision... but then we got rescued. The jeans are from Egypt. They are pregnancy trousers as I had just a few of months before the journey given birth to our youngest child. I also had a hijab but mine got ripped so I threw it away in Italy and a woman there gave me a new one. Underneath I wore this hairband. Iâ€™ve had it for many years and just accidentally wore it on the day we left Egypt but I still wear it today. Iâ€™m happy to be in Germany. All I want is a safe future and a good education for my children. Crimes Of The Land It is impossible for a wave to catch fire and burn. There are no mines hidden in ebbing tides. There are no soldiers crouched in the surf. The nature of the sea will not invade your living room space, it will not erase cultures, rip out your phone line or massacre families. The sea wants healing. The sea gives salt. Whales no nothing of guns or drones, dolphins will not imprison or interrogate uncles, fish will not violate women and coral will not call you what you are not. The sea preserves with its depth and laments, its eyes a body of ancient tears. It offers its skin to those running, those fleeing what it has never been. It is life, future, escape. Its politics transparent, its rhetoric fluid. It calls for trembling hands. Fear is loaded and crammed on its back. Families huddled inside the shelter of prayer. 1069482492496362901_1963339014	8/09/2015 13:37		16	208	Clarendon	https://instagram.com/p/7XkKkavr2V/	"To Aylan Your sweet nothings They told me to whisper sweet nothings and to never mention pain and aches for words fly back they say seven times into your flesh And what about the sea and froth caressed by the sun, is it pretty enough? and wet skin of forsaken children on a summer night? what about dead little corpses on the white and blue shores? But ""them"" are always far, they say And they keep their sweet nothings, with those dead I(s) in their face and the grimace of their heart as they sigh of relief But I won't let you. Is that picture pretty? Indignation much? You do like your noises too. So listen, I'm grabbing your ears, and your neck, and your guts, and you shall hear the words of horror and cruelty for darkness to (h)it me and you too. Look, and feel, I command you, Feel the slippery hand, and the screams and gurgling of your drowning lungs, and die like the baby boy, and the children who were killed by the sweet nothings you chose to utter when ""them"", and ""they"", and ""us"" are still you, and me too. So let's talk of pain and aches, and scars, and slaves, and death, and rapes and tragedies that shock and hurt and take that darkness back at you, with me too For ""love is a deed we do"" not a sweet nothing and a smile. s.p. #poetoftheembrace __________________ I received an email telling me to feel good, that it's all about saying sweet nothings, and it drove me mad with anger, sweet nothings, in a world were a baby boy, and so many more die!!! 1068756409373082166_1578026711	7/09/2015 13:35	51.502923144, -0.092236046	0	10	Normal	https://instagram.com/p/7U_Eq0GsI2/	So far this year a staggering 188.000 people have put their lives into the hands of smugglers to take them across the Mediterranean to Europe. For my project 'Travelling Light' I have asked them about their journeys and the items they had with them and what these items mean to them. Mohammad Majid, 52, Car Mechanic I bought this jacket in a shopping mall in Damascus about four years ago. I like it. Itâ€™s real leather. It used to always be a very smart jacket but now it got torn on the journey and the rain and the water spolit the leather. In order to reach the boat we all had to walk through the water. It was nearly up to my neck. All I could carry was my son. My bag with all my belongings I had to leave behind. All my clothes were wet. Also this leather jacket. So we sat on the boat with no dry clothes to change into and it was so cold. We all got sick. We started our trip in Alexandria. 576 people were on the ship. it had two floors but the basement was full of water, so nobody could go there. One of the engines was broken and the second one wasnâ€™t working properly either so we repaired it ourselves. Eventually we had to change ships in the middle of the sea. 400 got on one ship and the others onto a small wooden fishing boat. After two days we changed again and got onto another, bigger boat. There were already people on it. They had no water and only moldy bread. Some people didnâ€™t want to get on this ship but the smugglers threatened to kill them if they refused. The people who were already on the ship had been waiting for us for eight days and were in a terrible state. Changing ships in the middle of the sea was scary. The constant movement of the waves made it difficult to catch the right moment. Some fell into the water but nobody drowned. We even managed to get two people in wheelchairs across. First the people, then the chairs. I was very scared. It was the journey of death. #travellinglightproject #WeAreAllHumans #refugeeswelcome #syriansineurope #worldrefugeeday #crisis #humanitywashedashore #refugeecrisis #aylan #reportagespotlight #flakphoto #theguardian	https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/hphotos-xtf1/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/10890685_1652239745020756_233697776_n.jpg	weareallhumans, travellinglightproject, theguardian, reportagespotlight, humanitywashedashore, syriansineurope, refugeeswelcome, worldrefugeeday, refugeecrisis, flakphoto, crisis, aylan	sonicetobeme	1578026711

1068677641536790366_44023318	7/09/2015 10:58		4	49	Normal	https://instagram.com/p/7UtKcjM99e/	LINK IN BIO ----- ğŸ‘‡ READ ğŸ‘‡ 1 - Refugee appeal, taking the aid to where it's needed. Life is too precious to watch our kids drown or die from hunger. We can not bring them here to ensure their wellbeing, the least we can do is help where possible. As the need has dramatically increased, we are pushing out refugee displacement programs and will need your help to make them happen. Recently we have been advised that with winter coming there will be a major problem with clothing, we have put together close to 100 000 items with a total value well over 2-300, 000 dollar mark. We need your help to get these products to the border of Syria and Lebanon. The items we have collected have been a combined effort in Australia and have gone through strict sorting rules. These items could save thousands upon thousands of people. Items include blankets, pillows, jumpers, clothes, socks, ladies underwear, nappies, ladies pads, toothbrushes and amenities. These can be viewed at any time by anyone wishing to donate. We have a huge amount of goods and these have been donated at no cost to the refugees. To ensure these products get to the correct people there is a need to personally oversee everything, we have been months talking with various sources in regards to accepting and dispatching the products but unfortunately the local governments charge large taxes. We have spoken to Red Cross and various other agencies who told us they don't have the resources to complete such tasks and will not take clothes and amenities. These items are incredible, people were really generous and donated incredible things. We don't want them getting into the wrong hands, so please help us. We have been also asked if possible to supply wheelchairs, mobility beds and crutches as there is increasing amount of injured refugees. Cost of container is $5200 estimated cost of taxes between $10-15000 depending on what happens on the ground and how local government label the items. 1068003906852803209_1495098123	6/09/2015 12:40		7	28	Normal	https://instagram.com/p/7ST-UOsNKJ/	"The ultimate injustice one can commit to #Aylan Kurdi and his family is to omit the parts of his story which explain why he ended up dead on the beach. While in detention, he was tortured and his teeth were pulled out. He had to sell his shop in Damascus in order to bribe the officers to let him out. This cost him 5,000,000 Syrian Liras (around $25,000) . .2) After he bribed his way out of jail, Abdullah fled to Aleppo with his wife and sons, Alyan and Ghalib. The situation in Aleppo became dangerous due to the constant aerial bombardment, so he fled again to Kobani, his hometown. . 3) When ISIS attacked Kobani last year, the family could no longer live in their hometown, so they fled to Turkey. Once in Turkey, the Turkish government did not provide them with assistance, so they paid almost $6,000 to secure 4 spots on a rubber dingy to the Greek island of Kos. . 4) While on the boat, rough waters caused the boat to flip. The lifejackets they were given were fake. His sons and wife all drowned in front of his eyes, in his arms. . 5) Kurdi had applied in June for refuge to Canada, but was rejected. After Aylan's photo became a media story, he was reportedly offered citizenship to Canada. But he doesn't want to go to Canada or Europe anymore. He says he will go bury his family in Kobani and stay there to fight against ISIS, because everything has been taken away from him and he has ""nothing to live for."" . .So if the world wants to no more Aylans on the beach, someone needs to do some combination of the following based on above: (1) stop torture and arbitrary detention by the Assad regime, (2) stop the regime's aerial bombardment, (3) stop ISIS, (4) make traveling to Europe safe, (5) get Canada and the USA to accept more refugees.
